    "### Importing required libraries\n",
    "\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "from sklearn import datasets\n",
    "from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix\n",
    "from sklearn.decomposition import PCA\n",
    "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, OneHotEncoder\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, ConfusionMatrixDisplay, classification_report\n",
    "from sklearn.cluster import KMeans, DBSCAN\n",
    "from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression\n",
    "from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB\n",
    "from sklearn.svm import SVC"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4c95d731",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Data Preprocessing\n",
    "\n",
    "In this section, we will work with the [KDD Cup 99 dataset](https://kdd.ics.uci.edu/databases/kddcup99/kddcup99.html), a widely used benchmark for evaluating [**network intrusion detection**](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intrusion_detection_system) algorithms. This dataset contains simulated network traffic, including both *normal* connections and a small fraction of *attack* events.\n",
    "\n",
    "The dataset contains a mix of **continuous** and **categorical** features describing TCP connections, login attempts, and traffic patterns. Key feature categories include:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Basic connection features** – e.g., `duration`, `protocol_type`, `service`, `src_bytes`, `dst_bytes`, `flag`, `land`, `wrong_fragment`, `urgent`.  \n",
    "2. **Content features** – e.g., `hot`, `num_failed_logins`, `logged_in`, `num_compromised`, `root_shell`, `su_attempted`.  \n",
    "3. **Traffic features over a 2-second time window** – e.g., `count`, `srv_count`, `serror_rate`, `srv_serror_rate`, `rerror_rate`, `srv_rerror_rate`.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "### Load and Process the KDDCUP99 Dataset\n",
    "We’ll use the **SA subset** of the data to keep computation manageable. It contains mostly normal connections with a small fraction of attacks (~1–3%)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "d7946047",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "100655 datapoints with 3377 anomalies (3.36%)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Load KDDCup99 dataset (subset for demonstration)\n",
    "X, y = datasets.fetch_kddcup99(\n",
    "    subset=\"SA\",             # Use the 'SA' subset (smaller sample)\n",
    "    percent10=True,          # Use 10% of the full dataset for efficiency\n",
    "    random_state=42,         # Ensure reproducibility\n",
    "    return_X_y=True,         # Return data and labels separately\n",
    "    as_frame=True            # Load as pandas DataFrame\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Convert binary label: 1 = attack, 0 = normal\n",
    "y = (y != b\"normal.\").astype(np.int32)\n",
    "\n",
    "n_samples, anomaly_frac = X.shape[0], y.mean()\n",
    "print(f\"{n_samples} datapoints with {y.sum()} anomalies ({anomaly_frac:.02%})\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8a567246",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "- We convert labels and predictions into **binary format**:  \n",
    "  - `0` → Normal  \n",
    "  - `1` → Anomaly"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ca5f3e30",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The SA dataset contains 41 features out of which 3 are categorical: `protocol_type`, `service` and `flag`. We will explicitly convert these columns to the category data type and ensure that all other features are treated as numeric."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "dcd52a7b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Ensure categorical columns are 'category'\n",
    "cat_columns = [\"protocol_type\", \"service\", \"flag\"]\n",
    "X[cat_columns] = X[cat_columns].astype(\"category\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Ensure numeric columns are float\n",
    "numeric_features = X.columns.difference(cat_columns)  # all other columns\n",
    "X[numeric_features] = X[numeric_features].astype(float)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Update categorical features in case dtype changed\n",
    "categorical_features = X.select_dtypes(include=[\"category\"]).columns\n",
    "numeric_features = X.select_dtypes(include=[\"number\"]).columns"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f9c33bba",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Before training a machine learning model, all categorical (non-numeric) features need to be converted into a numerical format. Here, we use **one-hot encoding** via `OneHotEncoder` from `sklearn.preprocessing`.  \n",
    "Numeric features are **standardized** using `StandardScaler` to have zero mean and unit variance. Finally, the processed numeric and categorical features are combined into a single array suitable for model training."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "88195bc7",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# One-hot encode categorical features\n",
    "encoder = OneHotEncoder(sparse_output=False, handle_unknown=\"ignore\")\n",
    "X_cat = encoder.fit_transform(X[categorical_features])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Standardize numeric features\n",
    "scaler = StandardScaler()\n",
    "X_num = scaler.fit_transform(X[numeric_features])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Combine processed numeric and categorical features\n",
    "X_processed = np.hstack([X_num, X_cat])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "74492331",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We split the dataset into **training (80%)** and **testing (20%)** subsets."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "a9c88ed8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Training samples: 80524\n",
      "Testing samples: 20131\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Split into training and test sets\n",
    "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(\n",
    "    X_processed, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42, stratify=y\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Print dataset sizes\n",
    "print(\"Training samples:\", len(X_train))\n",
    "print(\"Testing samples:\", len(X_test))"
   ]
  },
  {

  {

   "source": [
    "## Unsupervised Learning with the KDDCUP99 Dataset\n",
    "Unsupervised learning methods allow us to detect patterns and clusters in the network traffic dataset without using labels. In this section, we demonstrate **K-Means**, **DBSCAN**, and **Hierarchical Clustering** on PCA-reduced KDDCUP99 data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4301aa0c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### PCA (Principal Component Analysis)\n",
    "\n",
    "PCA is a linear dimensionality reduction technique that finds new orthogonal axes (principal components) along which the variance of the data is maximized.  \n",
    "> **Note:** It prioritizes directions where the data varies the most, since higher variance typically corresponds to more informative features."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "1d1b3232",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Reduce dimensionality for visualization\n",
    "pca = PCA(n_components=8)\n",
    "X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_processed)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9e666127",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Notes:**\n",
    "- PCA maximizes the variance captured in the reduced space.\n",
    "- Principal components are **uncorrelated** (orthogonal).\n",
    "- Often used for visualization, noise reduction, and improving clustering efficiency."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5a45a616",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### K-Means Clustering\n",
    "\n",
    "**Mathematical Idea:** <br>\n",
    "K-Means partitions $n$ points $\\{x_1, ..., x_n\\}$ into $k$ clusters $C_1,...,C_k$ by minimizing:\n",
    "\n",
    "$J = \\sum_{i=1}^{k} \\sum_{x \\in C_i} \\|x - \\mu_i\\|^2$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\mu_i$ is the centroid of cluster $C_i$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "7bf2fcca",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 600x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# K-Means with 2 clusters\n",
    "kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=2, random_state=42)\n",
    "kmeans_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(X_pca)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot K-Means clusters\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(6,6))\n",
    "plt.scatter(X_pca[:, 0], X_pca[:, 1], c=kmeans_labels, cmap='viridis', s=10)\n",
    "plt.title(\"K-Means Clustering (k=2)\")\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"PC1\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"PC2\")\n",
    "plt.show()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "source": [
    "Notes:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **K-Means** partitions data into $k$ clusters based on similarity.\n",
    "- Each point is assigned to the nearest cluster centroid.\n",
    "- Requires specifying the number of clusters $k$ which is often done using the [Elbow Method](https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/machine-learning/elbow-method-for-optimal-value-of-k-in-kmeans/).\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b6da700d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### DBSCAN – Density-Based Spatial Clustering\n",
    "\n",
    "DBSCAN is a non-parametric clustering algorithm which clusters points based on density:\n",
    "- A point is a **core point** if at least `min_samples` points are within `eps` distance.\n",
    "- **Border points** are reachable from core points.\n",
    "- **Noise points** are those not reachable from any core point.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "6e899999",
   "metadata": {},

    {

    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# DBSCAN clustering\n",
    "dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=0.5, min_samples=25)\n",
    "dbscan_labels = dbscan.fit_predict(X_pca)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot DBSCAN clusters\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(6,6))\n",
    "plt.scatter(X_pca[:, 0], X_pca[:, 1], c=dbscan_labels, cmap='plasma', s=10)\n",
    "plt.title(\"DBSCAN Clustering\")\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"PC1\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"PC2\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]

    "- **DBSCAN** groups points based on density.\n",

    "- Does not require specifying the number of clusters (non-parametric).\n"
   ]

  {

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Supervised Learning with the KDDCUP99 Dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "In this section, we will demonstrate **classic supervised learning algorithms** that require labeled data, specifically **Logistic Regression** and **Naive Bayes**, to detect attacks in network traffic."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5920d85e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Logistic Regression\n",
    "Logistic Regression is a classic supervised learning algorithm used for **binary classification** tasks. \n",
    "\n",
    "**Mathematical Idea:**\n",
    "\n",
    "Logistic Regression models the probability that a given input belongs to a class using the logistic (sigmoid) function:\n",
    "\n",
    "$P(y=1 \\mid \\mathbf{x}) = \\sigma(\\mathbf{w}^\\top \\mathbf{x} + b) = \\frac{1}{1 + \\exp(-(\\mathbf{w}^\\top \\mathbf{x} + b))}$\n",
    "\n",
    "where:\n",
    "- $\\mathbf{x}$ is the feature vector,\n",
    "- $\\mathbf{w}$ are the model weights,\n",
    "- $b$ is the bias term,\n",
    "- $\\sigma(\\cdot)$ is the sigmoid function mapping any real number to $[0,1]$.\n",
    "\n",
    "The model is trained by minimizing the **binary cross-entropy loss**:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\\mathcal{L} = -\\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{i=1}^{N} \\left[ y_i \\log \\hat{y}_i + (1-y_i) \\log (1-\\hat{y}_i) \\right]$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\hat{y}_i = P(y=1 \\mid \\mathbf{x}_i)$ and $y_i \\in \\{0,1\\}$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "5967b291",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

   ]

    "\n",

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Gaussian Naive Bayes\n",
    "\n",
    "Gaussian Naive Bayes is a classic supervised learning algorithm based on **Bayes’ theorem** and the assumption that features are conditionally independent given the class label.  \n",
    "\n",
    "**Mathematical Idea:**\n",
    "\n",
    "For a feature vector $\\mathbf{x} = [x_1, x_2, \\dots, x_d]$ and a class $y \\in \\{0,1\\}$, Gaussian Naive Bayes models the class conditional probability as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$P(\\mathbf{x} \\mid y) = \\prod_{j=1}^{d} P(x_j \\mid y)$\n",
    "\n",
    "Assuming each feature $x_j$ follows a Gaussian distribution for class $y$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$P(x_j \\mid y) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2 \\pi \\sigma_{y,j}^2}}\\exp\\left(-\\frac{(x_j - \\mu_{y,j})^2}{2 \\sigma_{y,j}^2}\\right)$\n",
    "\n",
    "where:\n",
    "- $\\mu_{y,j}$ is the mean of feature $x_j$ for class $y$,\n",
    "- $\\sigma_{y,j}^2$ is the variance of feature $x_j$ for class $y$.\n",
    "\n",
    "The predicted class $\\hat{y}$ is obtained using Bayes’ theorem:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\\hat{y} = \\arg\\max_y P(y) \\prod_{j=1}^{d} P(x_j \\mid y)$\n",
    "\n",
    "Gaussian Naive Bayes is particularly fast and works well for high-dimensional numeric data.\n"
   ]
  },

  {

   "source": [
    "### Support Vector Machine (SVM)\n",
    "\n",
    "Support Vector Machine (SVM) aims to find the optimal hyperplane that best separates the data into different classes.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Mathematical Idea:**\n",
    "\n",
    "Given a labeled dataset $(x_i, y_i)$, where $x_i \\in \\mathbb{R}^n$ and $y_i \\in \\{-1, +1\\}$, the SVM optimization problem is formulated as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\\min_{w, b} \\ \\frac{1}{2} \\|w\\|^2$\n",
    "\n",
    "subject to:\n",
    "\n",
    "$y_i (w \\cdot x_i + b) \\ge 1, \\quad \\forall i$\n",
    "\n",
    "Here:\n",
    "- $w$ is the weight vector perpendicular to the separating hyperplane.\n",
    "- $b$ is the bias term that shifts the hyperplane.\n",
    "- The decision boundary is given by $w \\cdot x + b = 0$.\n",
    "\n",
    "For non-linearly separable data, SVM uses the **kernel trick** to implicitly map input features into a higher-dimensional space where a linear separation becomes possible.\n",
    "\n",
    "Common kernels include:\n",
    "- **Linear kernel:** $K(x, x') = x \\cdot x'$\n",
    "- **Polynomial kernel:** $K(x, x') = (x \\cdot x' + c)^d$\n",
    "- **RBF (Gaussian) kernel:** $K(x, x') = \\exp(-\\gamma \\|x - x'\\|^2)$\n",
    "\n",
    "The predicted class $\\hat{y}$ for a test point $x$ is given by:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\\hat{y} = \\text{sign}(w \\cdot x + b)$\n",
    "\n",
    "SVMs are robust to high-dimensional spaces and effective when the number of features exceeds the number of samples.\n"
   ]
  },
